[2]
Date: Thu 13 Jun 2002
From: Pablo Nart <p.nart@virgin.net>
Source: Dominion (New Zealand) via Newsline, Sat 8 June 2002 [edited]

New Zealand: Increase in Travel-related Cases of Dengue Fever
-------------------------------------------------------------
More New Zealanders are falling ill with the potentially fatal dengue fever
after failing to take sufficient precautions against mosquito bites while
travelling in the tropics. Dengue fever is an acute mosquito-borne disease
which kills about 25 000 people a year world-wide from an estimated 20
million cases. Typical symptoms include high fevers, muscle aches,
vomiting, exhaustion and often depression, but a severe form, called dengue
hemorrhagic fever, can kill.
In New Zealand dengue fever has been relatively rare, with an average of 14
cases a year between 1995 and 2000. But public health researchers said the
incidence of the disease soared last year, with a record 93 cases reported.
Researchers at the Environmental and Science Research Institute said many
reasons had been suggested for an explosion of dengue fever world-wide,
including increased travel, urbanization, population growth, crowding,
poverty and weaker public health measures. But they remain puzzled by the
surge in cases in New Zealand. Even during the dengue pandemic of 1998
there were only 26 cases reported, which suggested the big number of cases
in New Zealand was not due to factors such as increased travel. Institute
researcher Rabia Khan said it was also not likely the increase was due to
improved diagnosis as an Auckland study had shown that even where a patient
had recently travelled to the tropics, doctors were not initially
considering dengue in making a diagnosis.
The country most commonly visited by dengue fever patients in New Zealand
was Samoa (59 cases), followed by Tahiti (8), Indonesia and Thailand (5
each), Cook Islands, The Tokelaus and East Timor (3 each), Philippines (2),
and Fiji, India and Sri Lanka (one each).
Dengue fever can be transmitted by the _Aedes egypti_, _Aedes albopictus_,
and _Aedes polynesiensis_ mosquitoes, and the first 2 have been among the
dozen interceptions of exotic mosquitos at the border since January 1998.
--
